{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_cinnabar_ver01/data/sn2008060405/00332898097/1910112501/0304.xml":{"full_text":"A Foe to Union ILalbor\nIn various ways and on many occasions the evil influence of the saloon has been recognized and pointed out by\nthe labor unions of the United States. While the liquor interests have sought to convey the impression that there\nwas some common interest between trade unionism and the manufacture and sale of intoxicants, this suggestion is\nrepelled on every occasion when the matter is presented to the labor men in its true light and when the malign pur\npose of the liquor interests is exposed to view.\nI have no sympathy with the statement, so often made, that the manufacture and sale of liquor has contributed\nto the industrial development of the nation. On the contrary, I believe that liquor has contributed more to the\nmoral, intellectual, and material deterioration of the people and has brought more misery to defenseless women\nand children than has any other agency in the history of mankind.\u2014John Mitchell, Labor Champion, in a letter\nwritten to the Very Reverend James E. Cassidy, Fall River, Mass.\nTHey Didn\u2019t Want Facts\nThe so-called Citizens Defense Committee of St. Louis, who\nfought to keep the breweries and saloons in St. Louis and\nMissouri, issued during the campaign which closed November\n7th an enormous1 amount of literature. Perhaps never in the\nhistory of this country was there such a mass of lying liter\nature placed before the people. Almost every booklet, cir\ncular and newspaper advertisement was a mass of lies. One\nbooklet was called \u201cA Letter from Worcester, Mass.\u201d In it\nwere the following statements:\nWorcester, Mass., is the largest city in the world which has\ntested prohibition of the sale of intoxicating liquors and bever\nages within its limits. This test continued from December, 1907,\nto December, 1909. The results were disastrous, as the following\namazing story will show:\nIn those two years, two thousand dives replaced one hundred\nand fifty orderly saloons.\nHospital records show that alcoholism increased.\nPolice court records show that drunkenness grew more common\nand that the percentage of women and children among the of\nfenders was vastly increased.\nUnited States interstate Commerce Commission records prove\nthat Worcester people drank more liquor per capita than in any\nlicensed city in the world.\nMore liquor was sold in Worcester than in any other two years\nin the city\u2019s history.\nWomen operated a majority of the dives and sixty-five per\ncent of the liquor offenders arraigned in the local courts were\nwomen.\nDrug stores, blind tigers and speak-easies sold the lowest\ngrades of liquor.\nTrade went to other cities and Worcester had the worst period\nof business depression in its history.\nRobert H. Maywood, secretary of the Massachusetts No\nLicense League wrote a letter to each one of the fifty St.\nLouis men who were named as the executive committee of\nthe citizens Defense Committee and also to the St. Louis\npapers that published the statements about Worcester. In\nthis letter Mr. Maywood gave the following facts taken from\nthe official records of Worcester:\nFirst five months of license, 1910, compared with correspond\ning months of license years, 1900-1908, and no-license years,\n1908-1910.\nTotal Arrests\nLicense No License License\n1900 1907 1908 1909 1910\n2620 2832 1805 2203 2923\nDrunkenness\nLicense No License License\n1900 1907 1908 1909 1910\n1750 1869 714 1215 1901\nDischarged Without Arraignment\nLicense No License License\n1900 1907 1908 1909 1910\n917 1099 413 804 1339\nPatients in Alcoholic Ward\n(City Hospital)\nLicense No License License\n1900 1907 1908 1909 1910\n91 131 50 84 161\nNone of the St. Louis papers retracted the false statements\nspread about Worcester after the facts were sent them. The\nCitizens Defense Committee continued to distribute the book\nlet with its mass of lies after the facts were sent to the officers\nand executive committee of fifty.\nThe following is a copy of a letter sent by Mayor James\nLogan of Worcester to a correspondent seeking the truth:\nN. Johannes, Care N. Johannes Sons Implement Co., Nevada,\nMissouri.\nDear Sir\u2014I have your letter of October 18th, enclosing a\npamphlet sent out by the Citizens\u2019 Defense Committee of St. Louis.\nTo answer all the misstatements in that pamphlet would re\nquire more time than I can give to it at present. I can simply\nsay that never before have I seen so many misstatements con\ndensed into the same amount of space.\nIn my opinion, and in the opinion of all men unprejudiced by\npersonal interests, Worcester was cleaner under no-license than\nit has been for years under license, and considering the inter\nstate commerce law, conditions which we could not control, the\nno-license law was well enforced.\nThe conditions under no-license were betters than they are to\nday when the license law is being enforced as it never has been\nbefore.\nI am sending you today a copy of the Worcester Evenini7\nGazette, or at least two clippings from that paper, the said paper\nbeing one of the cleanest and most reputable newspapers in New\nEngland. You will note the record the first five months of the\npresent license year as compared with the past four years, two\nof which were under license and two imder no-license. This tells\nits own story. It needs no comment of mine. These are the facts.\nVery truly yours,\nJAMES LOGAN, Mayor.\nOne Witlhi God\n\u201cI arraign the rum traffic as the greatest curse the age has\nknown. Its pallor is on our nation and its blight is every\nwhere.\n\u201cYou may ask where do I stand. You have a right to\nknow.\n\u201cCreep up close to the heart of God who hates every evil\nthing. Ask Him where he stands and put me down on that\nside.\n\u201cOr if that is too nmch trouble, go to the poor pale faced\nwoman, the ragged and half starved children, the innocent\nvictims of the accursed traffic. Ask them where they stand\nand put me down there.\nOr if that is too much trouble, go out to your cemetery\nand creeping in among the graves of the victims of the\ndemon drink, ask yourself as you contemplate their ruin,\nwhere in the name of all that is holy, a man should stand.\nWhen you have your answer put me down there.\n\u201cI stand here tonight giving no quarter and asking none,\nconscious that I am sustained by heaven, endorsed by every\ngood woman and every honest man. But if I should stand\nalone here, I should stand, conscious that one with God is a\nmajority.\u201d\u2014Rev. Father McCorry.","height":"15867","width":"11934"}}
